From mid June through early July innumerable forest fires have burned
throughout the country's National Parks.  Many are small, just a few
acres, while others range from 1000 to more than 2000 acres.  Their
causes vary from lightening strikes to fireworks to hot vehicle
exhaust pipes.  The largest seems to be a fireworks-caused blaze that
swept over 2,200 acres near Yosemite National Park in California.
More than 670 firefighters from federal, state and local agencies
spent $384,000 to combat this fire, which is now under control.
Elsewhere, major fires occurred in Utah, Wyoming, Montana, Michigan,
Tennessee and Kentucky.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d22"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP880705-0018"
SELECTOR="D"
SUMMARIZER="B">     

Sixty Forest Service firefighters brought Michigan's four-day Hiawatha
National Forest fire under control after it burned 1100 acres of
woodlands.  Firefighters were brought in from several states over the
Fourth of July holiday to help fight the blaze. Elsewhere, overnight
rain helped limit the growth of the Shoshone National Forest fire in
Wyoming that has burned 1650 acres so far.  The rain provided a
reprieve to the 430 firefighters who are fighting the blaze from the
air with helicopters and three air tankers and on the ground with four
bulldozers.  Fires in Yosemite and Yellowstone National Parks are also
being contained.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d22"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP880705-0109"
SELECTOR="D"
SUMMARIZER="B">     

Firefighters battled holiday fires which have already blackened more
than 6000 acres of wilderness in California, Michigan, Montana,
Wyoming and Utah.  Illegal fireworks are blamed for the blaze that
swept over 2,200 acres of Stanislaus National Forest in California,
the scene of huge wildfires last summer.  In Utah's Zion National Park
fire, high winds fanned the flames out of control.  Michigan's
four-day Hiawatha National Park fire is being contained.  A fire,
which burned 8,700 acres in Arizona's Tonto National Forest, has been
reported extinguished.  Forest Service policy is to let fires burn
unless they threaten trails or structures, or spread outside
wilderness boundaries.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d22"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP880801-0195"
SELECTOR="D"
SUMMARIZER="B">     

Dale Smallwood is one of 125 Forest Service criminal investigators.
He primarily investigates arson at Missouri's Mark Twain National
Forest.  It is consistently among the five forest districts with the
worst arson problem and is about 90% higher than the national average.
Arsonist set 172 of this year's 296 Mark Twain fires.  Smallwood says
it is part of a southern tradition to illegally burn forests.  Local
subsistence farmers claim that fire helps control ticks, snakes and
disease and the encroachment of trees where cattle graze.
Aesthetically, they like the smell of wood smoke and the look of a
"burned clean" forest.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d22"
