SUMMARIZER="B">     

Forest fires are burning in seven western states, specifically,
California, Idaho, Montana, Oregon, Utah, Washington and Wyoming.  In
Alaska, all fires are now inactive.  The most threatening of seventeen
major blazes in Idaho broke through a control line and raced to within
a mile of ranches and grain fields.  Montana's governor said 5,000
firefighters there are in their third week of duty.  He put the
firefighting cost at $15 million.  Officials closed areas of parkland
throughout the west due to fire risk.  The U.S.  Forest Service,
predicting a hot and dry Labor Day weekend, is closing additional
areas.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d22"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="WSJ880923-0163"
SELECTOR="D"
SUMMARIZER="B">     

Controversy exists as to what is best: allowing natural reforestation
after a forest fire, or promoting human intervention to speed up
"getting the forest green again."  In either case, everyone agrees
that post-fire recovery enables more and different plant, bird and
animal species to flourish in the forest for about 40 years until it
again matures and canopies over.  Also controversial is The National
Park Service's 16-year-old "natural burn" policy, which allows
lightening-caused forest fires to burn themselves out, except where
they threaten towns or park buildings.  Critics claim it was this
policy that enabled fires to destroy half of Yellowstone's 2.2 million
acres.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d22"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP881216-0017"
SELECTOR="D"
SUMMARIZER="B">     

A panel, assembled last September after the worst fire season ever in
Yellowstone National Park, recommended a temporary halt to the
government's "let it burn" forest fire policy.  The panel's
recommendation, made to the Secretaries of Agriculture and Interior,
stipulates that no fires be allowed to burn freely in national parks
and wilderness areas until the Forest Service and National Park
Service improve and strengthen their fire management plans.  These
responsible agencies must use a common vocabulary to develop standards
and policies, train employees in them and agree beforehand what will
be done if fires move across administrative boundaries.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d22"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA070189-0080"
SELECTOR="D"
SUMMARIZER="B">     

2300 firefighters now control an 8,200-acre brush fire in the
Cleveland National Forest in Riverside County, California.  It
destroyed 11 structures near Lake Elsinore.  The cost of fighting the
blaze may exceed $1.5 million and structural damage could be more than
$1.1 million.  The fire appears to have been caused by people near a
roadside store across the Orange County line.  Investigators appealed
for help to identify those responsible.  Elsewhere, a brush fire that
burned 2000 acres in the Antelope Valley is now contained.  The fire
claimed six structures including one home.  More than 1000 people were
forced to temporarily evacuate.</SUM>

<SUM
